    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Creatine Gummies for Beginners</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Are creatine gummies effective for beginners?</summary><p>Yes. A 2023 study confirmed that creatine gummies produced equivalent muscle creatine increases and performance improvements compared to powder when matched for dose. The key is getting 3-5g daily, regardless of format. For beginners, gummies eliminate mixing hassles and dosing errors.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Do beginners need a creatine loading phase?</summary><p>No. Taking 3-5g daily achieves full muscle saturation within 3-4 weeks without loading. Loading (20g/day for 5-7 days) is faster but causes bloating and GI discomfort. With gummies, loading would also require 12-20 gummies per day — expensive and impractical.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>How many creatine gummies should a beginner take per day?</summary><p>Follow the label. Most products provide 3-5g per serving in 2-5 gummies. Under 150 lbs, 3g is sufficient. Over 150 lbs, 5g is optimal. Check the supplement facts panel — per-gummy dose varies between brands.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Is creatine safe for beginners?</summary><p>Creatine monohydrate has over 500 studies confirming safety at 3-5g daily. The ISSN states it has no adverse effects on kidney function, liver function, or hydration in healthy individuals. The only documented effect is 1-3 lbs of water weight gain from intracellular hydration.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>When should beginners take creatine gummies?</summary><p>Timing matters less than consistency. Take them at the same time daily — with breakfast, post-workout, or before bed. Research shows a slight advantage to post-workout timing, but the difference is marginal. Daily consistency is what matters.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Do creatine gummies cause water retention or bloating?</summary><p>Creatine causes intracellular water retention (water pulled into muscle cells), not subcutaneous bloating. At maintenance doses (3-5g), most beginners experience no noticeable bloating. The 1-3 lbs of weight gain is from hydrated muscle cells — a desirable effect.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the difference between creatine monohydrate and HCl?</summary><p>Monohydrate has 500+ studies. HCl has fewer than 20. The ISSN recommends monohydrate as the gold standard. HCl is more water-soluble and may cause less GI discomfort, but its claimed superiority at lower doses is unproven. Beginners should default to monohydrate.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Can women take creatine gummies?</summary><p>Absolutely. A 2021 review in Nutrients found creatine equally effective in women for exercise performance, cognitive function, and bone health. Women typically start with 3g daily. Creatine does not cause masculine bulking — that myth is outdated.</p></details>

    <!-- WARN BOX -->
    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Important:</strong> While creatine is safe for healthy adults, individuals with pre-existing kidney disease should consult their physician before supplementation. Creatine increases creatinine levels (a kidney function marker), which can be misinterpreted on blood tests if your doctor is unaware you supplement. Inform your healthcare provider that you take creatine before any lab work.</p>
    </div>

